title.narrative: ADOLESCENT HEALTH

description.narrative: The Government demonstrates strengthened capacity to ensure adolescent have improved access to gender-responsive and culturally- competent physical, mental, sexual and reproductive health services and information, which contributes to Adolescent Empowerment, Adolescent Empowerment (Covid), Adolescent Health And Nutrition, Cross-Sectoral Communication For Development, Cross-Sectoral Monitoring, Data And Situation Analyses, Evaluation And Research, Hiv Prevention, Skills Development, Treatment And Care Of Children Living With Hiv. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Public Engagement, Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Evaluations, Research And Data, Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, United Nations Working Together. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2023, more children, adolescents and women, particularly the most vulnerable, benefit from improved and equitable neonatal, child, maternal and adolescent health and nutrition services, and adopt healthy life practices.

description.narrative: Multi-sectoral contributions of the National Adolescent and Youth Heath and Development Technical Working Group members have led to improved quality and increased number of Level III standards adolescent-friendly health facilities across the country. Likewise, policy development and government planning processes towards improved health outcomes of adolescents were enhanced through evidence-generation of the Committee on Children and HIV/AIDS especially around topics on mental health problems, sexual abuse, HIV and teenage pregnancy. Furthermore, partnerships were strengthened for meaningful adolescent engagements, and to scale up adolescent and youth-led community health projects that foster entrepreneurial mindset and innovations. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:07/02/2020
